post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_7245404_7245602_0": {"length": 31, "quality": 0.9117647058823529, "section_id": 3227}}, "n3337": {"so_7245404_7245602_0": {"length": 31, "quality": 0.9117647058823529, "section_id": 3100}}, "n4659": {"so_7245404_7245602_0": {"length": 30, "quality": 0.8823529411764706, "section_id": 3984}}}, "7245404": {"ViewCount": "8526", "Body": "<p>I recently find out that there is a reference-to-function concept in C++ :).\nSo as there are pointer-to-function and pointer-to-member-function different types. The question arises. Is there a \"reference-to-member-function\" concept?</p>\n<p>I tried to compile the following code, but GCC 3.4.6 gives an error.</p>\n<pre><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;\n\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass A {\npublic:\n  virtual void Af() const {\n    cout &lt;&lt; \"A::Af()\" &lt;&lt; endl;\n  }\n};\n\nint main() {\n  typedef void (A::&amp; MemFnc)() const;\n  MemFnc mf = &amp;A::Af;\n\n  A a;\n  (a.*mf)();\n\n  return 0;\n}\n</code></pre>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "7245602", "Title": "Reference to member function?", "CreationDate": "2011-08-30T15:09:38.537", "Id": "7245404", "CommentCount": "3", "PostTypeId": "1", "ClosedDate": "2014-02-22T23:11:24.400", "LastActivityDate": "2011-08-30T15:31:11.303", "Score": "15", "OwnerUserId": "653478", "Tags": "<c++><function-pointers>", "AnswerCount": "3"}, "7245605": {"Id": "7245605", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>No, references to member functions are not possible.</p>\n<p>In some sense, the result of dereferencing a pointer to a member function could serve as one, but the <em>only</em> thing you can do with that result is to invoke a function call operator on it, per <code>5.5[expr.mptr.oper]/6</code>. Nothing else is allowed.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-08-30T15:20:49.203", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2011-08-30T15:20:49.203", "ParentId": "7245404", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "273767"}, "7245534": {"Id": "7245534", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>There is no reference to member function.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-08-30T15:17:04.433", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2011-08-30T15:17:04.433", "ParentId": "7245404", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "839436"}, "7245602": {"Id": "7245602", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>There is no such a thing called <em>reference to member</em> in C++.</p>\n<p>The language specification explicitly says <em>in a note</em> (\u00a78.3.3/3 - 2003) that,</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_7245404_7245602_0\">A pointer to member shall not point to a static member of a class (9.4), a member with reference type, or \u201ccv void.\u201d [Note: see also 5.3 and 5.5. The type \u201cpointer to member\u201d is distinct from the type \u201cpointer\u201d, that is, a pointer to member is declared only by the pointer to member declarator syntax, and never by the pointer declarator syntax. <strong>There is no \u201creference-to-member\u201d type in C++.</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "415784", "LastActivityDate": "2011-08-30T15:31:11.303", "Score": "20", "CreationDate": "2011-08-30T15:20:43.197", "ParentId": "7245404", "CommentCount": "9", "OwnerUserId": "415784", "LastEditDate": "2011-08-30T15:31:11.303"}});